{% extends "layouts/base.njk" %}
{% import "partials/_demo.njk" as ui %}

{% block title %}Architecture · Stisla{% endblock %}

{% block content %}
  <header>
    <h1>Architecture</h1>
    <p class="lead">How the vanilla implementation is built. Read this when you want to understand what&rsquo;s inside the bundle, extend a component, or write a new implementation against the same spec.</p>
  </header>

  <section>
    <h2>What this page covers</h2>
    <p>Stisla is a design specification with multiple implementations planned. This page documents the vanilla implementation specifically. The pieces of the vanilla impl that have to be the way they are because of the spec live in <a class="link" href="/specification">Specification</a>. The pieces that exist to let users tune the system live in <a class="link" href="/customization">Customization</a>. The choices behind avoiding Bootstrap, Tailwind, and CSS-in-JS live in <a class="link" href="/why-stisla">Why Stisla</a>. This page covers the remaining ground. The shape of the packages, the layout of the source, the anatomy of a component file, and how the runtime is composed.</p>
    <p>Future implementations (React + Base UI, Vue + Reka, Svelte + bits-ui) get their own architecture pages when they land. The vanilla impl is the reference.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Two packages</h2>
    <p>Stisla ships in two scoped packages, installed and versioned together.</p>
    <div class="prose">
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th>Package</th><th>What it ships</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><code>@stisla/css</code></td><td>The universal stylesheet. Tokens, foundation, components, utilities. No JavaScript. Works in every implementation</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>@stisla/vanilla</code></td><td>The vanilla JavaScript runtime. Declares <code>data-stisla-*</code> behavior on the canonical markup. Pairs with <code>@stisla/css</code> at a matching version</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>The two share a version. <code>@stisla/vanilla</code> declares <code>@stisla/css</code> as a peer dependency pinned to the same release, so an out-of-sync pair fails at install time rather than at runtime. Future implementation packages (<code>@stisla/base-ui</code>, <code>@stisla/reka</code>, ...) each ship their own JS runtime alongside the same <code>@stisla/css</code>.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>CSS bundle composition</h2>
    <p>The compiled CSS is organized into four cascade layers, declared once at the top of every bundle entry:</p>
    {% call ui.code(lang='css') %}
@layer foundation, theme, components, utilities;
    {% endcall %}
    <p>Order matters. Foundation rules (reset, grid, typography baseline) sit below theme tokens. Theme tokens sit below component rules. Utilities sit on top so a utility class wins against the component it tweaks. Within layered scope, normal cascade rules apply.</p>

    <h3>What each layer holds</h3>
    <div class="prose">
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th>Layer</th><th>Contents</th><th>Source path</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><strong>foundation</strong></td><td>Normalize, Preflight reset, base typography rules, grid, container sizes</td><td><code>src/scss/foundation/</code></td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>theme</strong></td><td>The <code>:root { --st-* }</code> declarations and the dark-mode delta block</td><td><code>src/scss/tokens/_theme.scss</code></td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>components</strong></td><td>Every BEM component partial. One file per block</td><td><code>src/scss/components/_&lt;name&gt;.scss</code></td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>utilities</strong></td><td>The shipped utility classes (spacing, sizing, typography, surface)</td><td><code>src/scss/utilities/_utilities.scss</code></td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h3>Two bundle entries</h3>
    <p>Two pre-compiled bundles ship in <code>@stisla/css</code>. They share most of their content; the only difference is which optional components land in the build.</p>
    <div class="prose">
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th>Bundle</th><th>Includes</th><th>Use when</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><code>stisla.css</code> (core)</td><td>Every component except the vanilla-optional ones (carousel today)</td><td>You want the smallest install and pull optionals à la carte</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>stisla-full.css</code></td><td>Core plus every vanilla-optional component</td><td>You want one stylesheet that covers everything</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>The line between core and optional is a per-implementation decision. The spec doesn&rsquo;t fix it. Carousel is optional in vanilla because it depends on <code>embla-carousel</code>, a real install cost. A future React+Base UI bundle may include carousel in its default because its primitive library covers every Stisla component at a comparable weight. The <a class="link" href="/installation">Installation</a> page covers the picking rule from the user side; here it&rsquo;s a design choice in the bundle wiring.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Source layout</h2>
    <p>Every Stisla implementation reads from the same CSS source tree. The layout is flat by intent. Every spec&rsquo;d component lives next to every other, regardless of whether one implementation classifies it as core or optional.</p>
    {% call ui.code(lang='text', title='src/scss/') %}
src/scss/
  tokens/          _theme.scss            (the --st-* token surface)
                   _breakpoints.scss      (Sass-only breakpoint map)
  foundation/      _normalize.scss        (vendored modern-normalize)
                   _reboot.scss           (Preflight reset, prose-restored)
                   _typography.scss       (base type rules)
                   _grid.scss             (.row + .col, BS-forked)
                   _containers.scss       (.container, .container-fluid)
                   _mixins.scss           (form-field-base, media-up, ...)
  components/      _btn.scss, _card.scss, _dialog.scss, ...
                   one file per block. ~45 files
  utilities/       _utilities.scss        (single file, config-driven)
  bundles/         stisla.scss            (core entry)
                   stisla-full.scss       (core + vanilla-optional)
                   components/<name>.scss (à-la-carte entries)
    {% endcall %}
    <p>The JS source mirrors the same shape:</p>
    {% call ui.code(lang='text', title='src/js/') %}
src/js/
  core/            component.js           (base class, instance lookup)
                   init.js                (register, init, DOM scan)
                   inert.js, transition.js
  components/      dialog.js, drawer.js, dropdown.js, ...
                   one file per JS-coordinated component
  index.js         core bundle entry
  index-full.js    core + optional components entry
    {% endcall %}
    <p>The repo also carries the cross-implementation contract files at the root. <code>SPEC.md</code> holds the shared contract. <code>spec/components/&lt;name&gt;.md</code> holds the per-component contract (anatomy, states, behavior, a11y, tokens) that every implementation honors. <code>V3.md</code> is the build journal for this vanilla impl.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Anatomy of a component file</h2>
    <p>Every component partial follows the same canonical shape. The patterns below come from <code>_card.scss</code>, which is small enough to read end to end.</p>

    <h3>1. Header comment</h3>
    <p>What the file is, the BEM contract, the tokens it reads. The first thing a reader sees.</p>
    {% call ui.code(lang='scss', title='_card.scss') %}
// Stisla — card.
//
// BEM: .card (root) + parts (__header / __body / __footer / __title /
// __subtitle / __text / __link / __image / __overlay). Variants stay
// flat on the root (.card--flat).
//
// Tokens: --st-surface (bg), --st-border, --st-card-radius -> --st-radius-lg
// (large-surface tier), --st-card-shadow -> --st-shadow,
// padding × var(--st-density).
    {% endcall %}

    <h3>2. Component-scoped variables on the root</h3>
    <p>Every visual decision goes through a <code>--&lt;block&gt;-*</code> variable declared on the root selector. The fallback chain reads <code>var(--st-&lt;name&gt;-*, var(--st-tier))</code> where applicable so a user can override globally at <code>:root</code> or per-instance via the local variable.</p>
    {% call ui.code(lang='scss', title='_card.scss') %}
.card {
  --card-radius:  var(--st-card-radius, var(--st-radius-lg));
  --card-padding: calc(1.25rem * var(--st-density));
  --card-shadow:  var(--st-card-shadow, var(--st-shadow));
  --card-bg:      var(--st-surface);
  --card-color:   var(--st-foreground);
  --card-border:  var(--st-border-width) solid var(--st-border);
  ...
}
    {% endcall %}
    <p>The variable surface comes first so a reader can scan the customization knobs without parsing rules. Layout properties (<code>display</code>, <code>position</code>, <code>padding</code>, ...) come after.</p>

    <h3>3. Parts via BEM element selectors</h3>
    <p>Every sub-element gets a <code>.&lt;block&gt;__&lt;element&gt;</code> class. No bare-element styling, no nested selectors that reach into specific HTML tags. Parts stay flat on the root&rsquo;s descendants.</p>
    {% call ui.code(lang='scss') %}
.card__body { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 0.5rem; padding: var(--card-padding); }
.card__header { ... }
.card__footer { ... }
    {% endcall %}

    <h3>4. Modifiers via flat block-level classes</h3>
    <p>Variants stay flat on the root (<code>.card--flat</code>, <code>.btn--primary</code>, <code>.alert--success</code>). Multiple modifiers compose; none nest.</p>
    {% call ui.code(lang='scss') %}
.card--flat {
  --card-shadow: none;
}
    {% endcall %}

    <h3>5. State derivation via <code>color-mix</code></h3>
    <p>Hover, active, and focus colors derive at runtime from a single source variable via <code>color-mix(in oklch, ...)</code>. The recipe percentages (88% for hover, 78% for active) live as Sass constants at the top of the component file. Same pattern across <code>.btn</code>, <code>.alert</code>, <code>.kbd</code>, <code>.list-group</code>, and a dozen others.</p>
    {% call ui.code(lang='scss', title='_btn.scss (excerpt)') %}
.btn:hover  { --btn-bg: color-mix(in oklch, var(--btn-tone) $btn-fill-hover, black); }
.btn:active { --btn-bg: color-mix(in oklch, var(--btn-tone) $btn-fill-active, black); }
    {% endcall %}
    <p>OKLCH mixing stays perceptually clean through the midpoints. The customization story (the <a class="link" href="/customization#state-derivation-and-escape-hatches">escape hatches</a>) covers when to bypass derivation per state.</p>

    <h3>6. State hooks</h3>
    <p>Runtime state is exposed through three vocabularies, each with a specific role.</p>
    <div class="prose">
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th>Hook</th><th>Use</th><th>Examples</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><code>[data-state="X"]</code></td><td>Primitive-library aligned state. Both Radix and Base UI use this convention. Stisla matches it so the same CSS serves the vanilla impl (which sets the attribute via its own JS) and the React/Vue impls (which inherit the attribute from their primitive library)</td><td><code>data-state="open"</code> on dialog, dropdown, drawer, popover. <code>data-state="active"</code> on tabs trigger</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>.is-&lt;state&gt;</code></td><td>Stisla-original states that no primitive library exposes a name for. Class-based so they sit alongside BEM modifiers and don&rsquo;t need a primitive-library mapping</td><td><code>.is-loading</code> on btn, <code>.is-collapsed</code> on sidebar</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>aria-*</code></td><td>Accessibility semantics. <code>aria-pressed</code>, <code>aria-current</code>, <code>aria-disabled</code>, <code>aria-expanded</code>. Reused as styling hooks when the visual treatment maps cleanly to the semantic</td><td><code>[aria-pressed="true"]</code> on btn for the pressed-in fill</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>The JavaScript runtime</h2>
    <p>The vanilla runtime is small. Around 600 lines of our own JS plus three vendored primitives. Every interactive component follows the same lifecycle, and most behavior comes from declarative markup rather than imperative JS calls.</p>

    <h3>Primitives we vendor</h3>
    <div class="prose">
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th>Library</th><th>Used by</th><th>Why</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><a class="link" href="https://floating-ui.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Floating UI</a></td><td>dropdown, popover, tooltip</td><td>Position calculation for floating elements (collision detection, placement flips, arrow rendering)</td></tr>
          <tr><td><a class="link" href="https://focus-trap.github.io/focus-trap/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">focus-trap</a></td><td>dialog, drawer</td><td>Keyboard focus containment inside overlays</td></tr>
          <tr><td><a class="link" href="https://www.embla-carousel.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Embla</a></td><td>carousel (optional)</td><td>Touch-friendly scroll mechanics. Lives in the optional bundle</td></tr>
          <tr><td><a class="link" href="https://kingsora.github.io/OverlayScrollbars/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">OverlayScrollbars</a></td><td>scroll-area</td><td>Custom-styled scrollbars that overlay the content without taking layout space</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>tabbable</code></td><td>focus-trap, sidebar dismiss</td><td>Walks the focusable tree. Tiny shared utility</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>Everything else comes from our own code. No jQuery, no Bootstrap JS bundle, no framework runtime.</p>

    <h3>The register and init pattern</h3>
    <p>Every component class registers under a string name. The core bundle entry registers them, then runs an auto-init on <code>DOMContentLoaded</code>. The init scan walks the DOM, finds elements matching <code>[data-stisla-&lt;name&gt;]</code>, and instantiates the component class for each match.</p>
    {% call ui.code(lang='js', title='src/js/index.js (shape)') %}
import { register, init } from './core/init.js';
import { Dialog } from './components/dialog.js';
import { Dropdown } from './components/dropdown.js';
// ...

register('dialog', Dialog);
register('dropdown', Dropdown);
// ...

if (document.readyState === 'loading') {
  document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => init());
} else {
  queueMicrotask(() => init());
}
    {% endcall %}
    <p>The auto-init runs in a microtask so an importer (e.g. <code>index-full.js</code> loading optional components on top of core) can call <code>register()</code> after the core module evaluates but before the scanner walks the DOM. The order stays deterministic.</p>

    <p>From markup, a consumer never calls JavaScript directly:</p>
    {% call ui.code(lang='html') %}
<div class="dialog" data-stisla-dialog id="confirm">...</div>
<button data-stisla-dialog-trigger="confirm">Open</button>
    {% endcall %}
    <p>The scanner picks both up, wires the trigger to the dialog, and exposes the instance via <code>Stisla.get(element)</code> if the consumer wants programmatic access later. Re-scanning is a single call (<code>Stisla.init()</code> again) so SPA frameworks that hydrate content after the first scan can rerun it. The <a class="link" href="/javascript">JavaScript</a> page covers the full API.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Preflight</h2>
    <p>The first thing the foundation layer ships is a reset that strips every default visual treatment from bare semantic elements. Headings, paragraphs, lists, <code>&lt;strong&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;small&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;a&gt;</code> all flatten to the body font and weight with no margins, no markers, no underlines.</p>
    <p>Visual treatment is opt-in via classes (<code>.h1</code>, <code>.fw-semibold</code>, <code>.kbd</code>). Long-form regions get element-level styling back inside a <code>.prose</code> scope (<code>.prose h2</code>, <code>.prose ul</code>, <code>.prose blockquote</code>).</p>
    <p>The reason is structural. Anything that styles an HTML tag at document scope is a global rule by definition, and a global rule reaches into every component that contains the element. Preflight removes those colliders so a component&rsquo;s CSS expresses only what the component contributes. A card footer with <code>&lt;small&gt;</code> inside doesn&rsquo;t pick up a surprise font size, and a button containing <code>&lt;strong&gt;</code> stays the button&rsquo;s own weight.</p>
    <p>A short list of element defaults survives where no class would ever opt in. <code>&lt;mark&gt;</code> carries the highlight tint, <code>&lt;abbr title&gt;</code> carries the dotted underline, <code>&lt;hr&gt;</code> carries a rule in <code>--st-border</code>, <code>:focus-visible</code> carries the ring in <code>--st-ring</code>. The reset is in <code>src/scss/foundation/_reboot.scss</code>.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>How this realizes the spec</h2>
    <p>The vanilla impl is one realization of the cross-implementation contract. Reading the spec alongside the vanilla source shows how each requirement lands in practice. A few examples:</p>
    <div class="prose">
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th>Spec requirement</th><th>Vanilla solution</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Token surface is <code>--st-*</code> only</td><td><code>src/scss/tokens/_theme.scss</code>. Only file with literal color values</td></tr>
          <tr><td>State derivation via <code>color-mix</code></td><td>Every component file. Recipe percentages as Sass constants at top of <code>_btn.scss</code> and similar</td></tr>
          <tr><td>BEM block names match the spec</td><td><code>.btn</code>, <code>.card</code>, <code>.dialog</code>, etc. One <code>_&lt;name&gt;.scss</code> per block</td></tr>
          <tr><td>State attributes match Radix conventions</td><td><code>[data-state="open|closed|active"]</code> set by our JS or by future primitive libraries; same CSS serves both</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Focus, dismiss, scroll-lock, keyboard a11y</td><td>focus-trap (dialog, drawer), our own dismiss + scroll-lock, Floating UI for floating elements</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Dark mode is one delta block</td><td>End of <code>_theme.scss</code>. <code>[data-theme="dark"]</code> and <code>.dark</code> both match</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Component contract per <code>spec/components/&lt;name&gt;.md</code></td><td>Each JS-coordinated component honors the spec&rsquo;s required behavior, parts, and events</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>Future implementations (React + Base UI, Vue + Reka, Svelte + bits-ui) get their own architecture pages with the same shape. Same spec, different runtime, different primitive library, same <code>@stisla/css</code> underneath.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>What&rsquo;s next</h2>
    <p>Read the <a class="link" href="/specification">Specification</a> for the cross-impl contract that every implementation honors. Read <a class="link" href="/customization">Customization</a> for the token table and the worked examples of the override model. Open any component file under <code>src/scss/components/</code> for the canonical pattern in practice; the <code>_btn.scss</code>, <code>_card.scss</code>, and <code>_alert.scss</code> files are the cleanest references.</p>
  </section>
{% endblock %}
